n.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> You will be able to see that in their reply to this FOI request, </span><a href="https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/customer_survey#comment-45518"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/customer_survey#comment-45518</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PHSO confirmed that an on-line customer survey would be up and running in the first quarter of 2014, which gives the answer to the ‘time-scale’ question which Helen Hughes found so difficult to answer. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is the opinion of the Pressure Group that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">all users</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the service should be supplied with the opportunity to complete a customer satisfaction survey, including those who do not have on-line access, to bring PHSO in line with good practice. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are not convinced by the high satisfaction rates stated by the Ombudsman.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> These figures do not match our experience in any way.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Taking a sample for analysis will always provide an opportunity to manipulate the data.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Only total coverage will reveal the true picture.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Dame Julie Mellor stated that, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘As a leader there’s nothing like listening to people yourself and I have spent a large part of the last two years listening to our customers myself.’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All members of our group have written directly to Dame Julie Mellor and had our letters ignored.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> One member sent a letter and two follow up emails in order to arrange a meeting with Dame Julie.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> She wrote the first letter in August, but did not receive any acknowledgement until December when she opened a FOI on this subject.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The truth of the matter is that the vast majority of correspondence which is addressed to Dame Julie Mellor never reaches her personally and is filed under ‘no action required’ by other staff.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This FOI requests shows just how difficult it is to have any direct contact with Dame Julie Mellor. </span><a href="https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/contacting_board_level_managemen"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/contacting_board_level_managemen</span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Pressure Group would like to know why there was ever such a high threshold of evidence required to trigger an investigation in the first place.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The onus should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be on the sufferer of the injustice to gather all the evidence.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The Ombudsman is aware that organisations obfuscate and deny access to evidence such as medical records and correspondence and spoke of such when she described the ‘toxic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cocktail’ delivered to complainants.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The reason the Ombudsman has the authority of a high court judge is so that her office can obtain the evidence which has been denied to the complainant.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The Committee heard that in Scotland the Ombudsman investigates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">every case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which meets submission criteria.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is the only fair way to provide justice and remedy and we would like to see this approach taken up by PHSO.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In relation to the delay in complaint handling which was also raised by the Committee, in Scotland a complainant can approach the Ombudsman 20 days after making their initial complaint which ensure that public bodies cannot simply ‘drag their feet’ to avoid dealing with serious issues.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We would also like to see this 20 day rule.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Unfortunately, even with the reduced threshold the three point criteria for investigation described by Dame Julie Mellor is likely to fail at point 2, finding ‘evidence of maladministration or service failure.’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This is because PHSO </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">systematically deny or manipulate the evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to find that public bodies have acted ‘reasonably’.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Dame Julie Mellor stated that these criteria were based in law, yet when a complainant sent evidence in support of her case provided by a specialist barrister confirming that three legal breaches had occurred the Ombudsman dismissed this evidence as mere ‘subjective opinion’.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is difficult to believe that the assessors are able to investigate 8x more cases with no additional resources.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Many of these cases are extremely complex.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is our strong suspicion that ‘assessments’ are now termed ‘investigations’ in order to meet this target with very little change in the process.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This is just not good enough. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mr. Mulholland went to great lengths to establish how often the Ombudsman found that on review of a case they had made a mistake and were willing to rectify this.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The answer from Dame Julie Mellor was in our opinion unclear.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This quote from the Resource Account for 2011 – 2012 gives a better indication of the chance that PHSO will rectify mistakes following review.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As PHSO have a remarkable 99.6% accuracy rate there are clearly few mistakes to rectify.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Georgia; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘For most people coming to us, our decision is the last opportunity to get things put right. We have built into our processes several checks and balances to ensure that our decisions are fair and robust. We give serious consideration to any complaints raised by our customers about our decisions and we seek to use the learning from these to improve our performance. In 2011-12 we found that 0.4% of our total decisions needed to be looked at again or required further explanation.’</span><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> (p9 from Resource Account 2011 – 2012 )</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Dame Julie Mellor stated that PHSO were the only organisation to use both internal and external reviewers to give independent and impartial decisions.</span><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">However, this FOI requests shows that there are only three external reviewers</span><span style="color:#373737; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A member of our group telephoned PHSO to confirm the use of ‘external’ reviewers and the response he received indicates the limited value of these ‘independent’ assessors to the general public. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">This morning I have called and spoken to PHSO Complaints reception point to try to establish / clarify / confirm the procedure for handling complaints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">PHSO, and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">measure of independence asserted to the PASC by JM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">on Monday 16th (watchable on-line).</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">For PHSO Complaints, there is an application form / address / phone number and procedure on PHSO website.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Emailed complaints will receive an automatic response which does not imply any actions of acceptance or process. Ditto for receipted letters.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Complaints against PHSO are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">not logged as new complaints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, and can't be tracked as such.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Complaints against PHSO are passed to the head of group of the action complained about, or the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">manager of the person named, for internal resolution. It is quite likely they will have knowledge of the case.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Although in effect complaints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">against</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">PHSO will be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">new complaints</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">i.e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> nothing to do with the reason the PHSO was contacted in the first place) they are not handled as such, they therefore inherit as 'properties' all the baggage and insensitivity of the injustice so far delivered. The Complaint will be linked to the original complaint of injustice.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">There will be no response if deemed unnecessary</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Complaints against PHSO procedure ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">e ignored because procedures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> be questioned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Despite the assurance given by JM to PASC, there actually is no independence in complaints - all complaints are vetted internally before any are selected for external review. An external review may not be necessary.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">It is not possible to contact an external reviewer if your complaint has not been selected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">by PHSO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">for external (albeit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">interested-party</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">by recruitment) review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">PHSO Complaints are unable to make a distinction between complainants unhappy with their 'decision', and the complainants who have been uninformed, misinformed, identified a procedural breakdown or abused literally, by a PHSO respondent. Either way - complainants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">can not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> be trusted to understand their concerns, condition or experience.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Of most interest to our group was the discussion between Mr. Mulholland and Dame Julie Mellor where she was asked for ‘explanations’ regarding the cases of complaint which had been put before the Committee.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> At this point Dame Julie Mellor asserted that she was accountable to the court for her decisions and to Parliament for her services, leaving no doubt that she was unaccountable to the Select Committee or to the individual complainants.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is a sorry state of affairs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We all know that the Ombudsman is not actually accountable by law due to the discretionary powers embedded in the 1967 act. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Only one case has ever been won against the Ombudsman, the remarkable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Balchin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> family who fought for over 20 years.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In relation to her being accountable for her services to Parliament it is difficult to ascertain exactly what ‘Parliament’ is.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The Ombudsman is not accountable to Ministers, MPs, Select Committees or Civil Servants, so in what respect does the Ombudsman account for her services and to whom?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Regardless of Dame Julie Mellor’s assertions, the Pressure Group firmly believe that as a public servant the Ombudsman is accountable to members of the public, who at the end of the day, pay the bill.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> We will not be satisfied until our genuine concerns have been addressed and resolved.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">19</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>